Palestine responds to Israel: We will break all agreements so far
Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas said Thursday at a session of the U.N. General Assembly that he would break all agreements with Israel if the country's future government tried to comply with Benjamin Netanyahu's announcement of the annexation of the occupied Palestinian lands.
“If the future government of Israel that arises proceeds to implement this plan, we will invalidate all signed agreements (with Israel) and withdraw from all commitments made,” he said.
“We will reject the whole plan completely and completely,” Abbas threatened with emphasis.
"It is our duty to defend all our rights by all possible means - of little importance, what the consequences will be - by engaging entirely in action for the application of international law and in the fight against terrorism," declared the Palestinian Authority President, who had already made similar declarations in July.
Netanyahu, Israel's former prime minister, was once again given a mission to form a government after the September 17 election.
A week before the election, he announced that if he won them, he would announce the annexation of the Jordan Valley and intend to include all Jewish settlements in Israel throughout the West Bank.
In the early 90's. Israel and the Palestinians, led by Yasser Arafat at the time, signed a series of peace agreements, which were patronized by the United States.
Abbas, 84, also promised to hold a general election on Palestinian soil during the U.N. General Assembly session.
The last one was in 2006.
“After returning to the country, I will call local elections in the West Bank, in Gaza and East Jerusalem, and all those who oppose them will have to answer for their actions before God and the international community,” the Palestinian president declared solemnly.
Abbas also defended in his speech the rights of Palestine, treated as a permanent observer at the United Nations, to exercise the powers of "full-fledged members of the United Nations and all its bodies and institutions."
The Palestinian leader concluded his speech to the international community with a call to "force Israel to fulfill with all respect for the provisions of the United Nations."
Israeli Ambassador Danny Danon responded briefly to Abbas's speech, declaring that the Palestinian leader "willingly focus at the United Nations on the Palestinian Authority's efforts against Israel than to fight against calls for terrorism in Autonomy under his leadership."
