105 million PLN for companies from the video game industry from the National Centre for Research and Development
Almost 105 million PLN of funding will go to companies from the gaming industry, creating innovative solutions.
The National Centre for Research and Development announced on Friday the results of the 3rd edition of the GameINN program.
Among the nearly 30 projects that NCBR supported, there was a m.in. development of a platform for creating off-road games based on the AR game engine creating a map of the real world with an application enabling the transfer of data by users; a test and training platform for verifying practical skills at the workplace and professional development with the use of VR and AI technology; an innovative game simulating the management of real production processes using an innovative gameplay model based on the virtual world
The aim of the GameINN sectoral program is to increase the competitiveness of the Polish sector of video game manufacturers on the global market in the perspective of 2023.
According to the NCBR, the Polish video game sector is already growing at a rate of 10% per year.
According to government data, the value of the Polish video game market in 2016 amounted to 1.85 billion PLN, while the forecast for 2019 was 2.23 billion.
“The specially prepared GameINN research agenda and the support for entrepreneurs already reaching 300 million PLN under this sectoral programme provide an important impulse for the further, dynamic growth of the Polish gamedev,” the company said.
The video game industry is a perfect example of effective use of the potential we have in Poland.
“The incentives introduced by the government for entrepreneurs focusing on innovation, such as R&D reliefs, competence improvement programs, IP box or support programs implemented by the NCBR drive the innovative activities of companies and allow them to compete more effectively in a very competitive market,” said Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of Science and Higher Education Jarosław Gowin, quoted in the release.
The head of the Ministry of Science points out that the money for innovation not only goes to innovators in the form of co-financing projects, but also stay in their pockets – three-quarters of more entrepreneurs benefited from the relief for R&D in 2018 than a year earlier.
“The amount of deducted costs related to R&D activities amounted to 1.7 billion PLN, which gave over 300 million PLN of savings for companies benefiting from this relief.
This is the equivalent of the support provided by the NCBR in three editions of GameINN," emphasizes the Deputy Prime Minister.
Director of NCBR Dr. Eng. Wojciech Kamieniecki reminds that in the previous two competitions co-financing with a total value of over 211.2 million PLN was awarded to 78 innovative projects.
The great interest in the third competition and the variety of proposals shown that the video game industry has ideas and competences to continue to develop and increase its competitive advantages.
“It is particularly welcome that among the selected projects – as in previous editions – there are projects concerning solutions for not only entertainment, but also related to industry 4.0,” he adds.
In the third GameINN competition, entrepreneurs, consortia of entrepreneurs and consortia with scientific units could apply for co-financing of up to 20 million PLN.
The NCBR received 87 applications for the total amount of funding approx. 317 million PLN.
The budget of the competition at the time of the announcement of the competition was 100 million PLN, but it was increased, thanks to which 27 projects were awarded almost 105 million PLN of funding.
Detailed information about the results of the 3rd GameINN competition is available at ncbr.gov.pl.
The GameINN sectoral programme is implemented under the Smart Growth Operational Programme.
NCBR launched the program in 2016 in response to the initiative of entrepreneurs affiliated to the Polish Games Agreement, which includes m.in. such companies as CD Projekt, Techland, CI Games, Bloober Team or 11 bit studios.
