UBS: Gold close to the equilibrium point
“The euro exchange rate will remain around the ceiling of 4.35 zlotys in the coming months, accompanied by a weak economic situation on global markets,” said Michael Bolliger from the company UBS Wealth Management.
“The expectations of maintaining a solid pace of economic growth and stable monetary policy are in favour of stabilizing the zloty’s quotations at the current ceiling,” the specialist said in an interview with Bankier.pl.
In his view, despite clear inflationary pressures, the Monetary Policy Council will not decide on rate hikes in an environment where the vast majority of central banks are easing policy.
“While the zloty is properly valued – euro quotations should remain in the coming months around the ceiling of 4.35 zlotys – according to him, Polish bonds are not attractive.
Much more favorable yields than Polish securities are offered by bonds from emerging markets," said Michael Bolliger, head of asset allocation to emerging markets in the company of UBS Wealth Management.
According to the specialist, the main threat to the Polish economy is the downturn in the world.
“The global slowdown may be even deepening, but there should be no severe recession, and at most a GDP dynamics below zero,” says Michael Bolliger.
“Investors should underestimate global stocks that could be harmed by the lack of prospects for a resolving trade conflict on the U.S.-China line and other geopolitical risk factors, including Donald Trump’s impeachment procedure and Brexit.
Among the stock markets, Europe should behave relatively weakest," according to the latest letter to investors by the main manager of UBS Wealth Management, Marek Haefele.
“Actions from eurozone countries should behave worse than the US, because they are more vulnerable in conditions of heightened uncertainty around global trade and fears of a slowdown,” the document reads.
According to Michael Bolliger, after the hossa in the bond markets of the safest countries pushed the yields of German 10-years even to minus 0.74 percent, it is still possible to deepen the decline in yields.
