The IUCN, an organisation based in Gland, Switzerland, publishes a list of endangered species of European trees for the first time.
It was prepared by specialists who, on the basis of research, concluded that out of the 454 species of trees found in Europe (as well as elsewhere in the world), 42 percent are "highly endangered."
Among the causes, the Red Paper lists the rapid growth of urban agglomerations and global climate change.
However, the most endangered are those trees and shrubs that occur only or mainly on our continent.
As for the typical European stand, according to IUCN specialists, 58 percent of species are threatened, and 15 percent, i.e. 66 species of trees and shrubs are in danger of extinction.
Among the main causes of deforestation, the Red Book lists errors in the operation of the stand, accelerated urbanization, too intensive felling of trees, and then forest fires and changes occurring in the European eco-stystem.
According to the authors of the report, the existence of many European varieties of shrubs, mosses and lichens is also strongly threatened.
“The consequences of human activity lead to the gradual disappearance of European plant species and pose a danger in Europe of the extinction of important and undervalued varieties that form the basis of European ecosystems and affect the health of our planet,” concluded report Luc Bas, who heads the European IUCN office.
