GUS: We are living better in Poland
According to the report published on Friday by the Central Statistical Office on household budgets, 44 percent of them assessed as a good or rather good financial situation last year.
A year earlier, that percentage was 37.2 percent, in 2016. 33.5 percent, and earlier – since 2009, when the statistics office first examined the subjective assessments of the situation of households – never exceeded 30 percent.
He considered his material situation to be bad or rather bad in the last year. A total of 8.1 percent of households, compared to 11.2 percent a year earlier and more than 20 percent in 2009.
The best is the financial situation of self-employed households.
In this group, more than 70% of respondents consider it to be good or rather good.
At the other pole are pensioners' households, where the percentage of such responses was just 18 percent.
The subjective assessment of the material situation of households is also greatly influenced by the number of children.
The worst thing is for parents raising offspring alone, among whom 32 percent declare a good or rather good material situation.
Among couples with children, this percentage varies (depending on the number of children) from 55 to 60 percent, and among childless households it is 48.8 percent.
In these statistics, the effect of the 500+ program is clearly visible.
Before it was launched (in 2016), the worst financial situation was assessed by single parents raising offspring and large families (with at least three children).
Improving subjective assessments of the financial situation of Poles is a reflection of the rapid growth of income, primarily from work.
However, this is not all, because the percentage of households that consider their situation to be good increases faster than real income.
Moreover, at the level of voivodships, there is no clear relationship between the level of income and the assessment of household material conditions.
The best assessments are formulated by the inhabitants of the Opole Voivodeship, where 48.9% of respondents consider their situation to be good or rather good.
Next are the Lubuskie (47.7%), Silesian (47.6%), Mazowieckie (47.3 percent) and West Pomeranian (47.1%) voivodships.
Meanwhile, in Opole, disposable income (i.e. after paying taxes and contributions) was less than 94 percent last year. national average, and in Lubuskie 98 percent.
The highest income was held by the inhabitants of Mazowiecki (120 percent. national average) and Silesian (104 percent).
On average, in Poland, disposable income per person was in 2018. 1693 zł.
In real terms (after the correction for the impact of price changes) it increased by 4.3 percent compared to 2017.
Compared to previous years, this is a fairly low result.
In 2016, personal income increased by 7 per cent, and a year later by 6.3 per cent.
Although income growth is slowing down, it also inhibits spending growth.
Those per person amounted to last year. 1187 zł, which means that in real terms they decreased by 0.7 percent.
This is the first such case since 2013.
In 2017, spending per person increased by 1.9 percent in real terms and by 4.3 percent in 2016.
Surveys of household budgets suggest that a statistical household now spends 70.1 percent of its disposable income, while in 2014 this share exceeded 80 percent, and by 2006 it exceeded 90 percent.
