"Rzeczpospolita": Ignoring the policeman's order will be punished
According to the newspaper, disregard of the order for a particular behavior issued by a police officer is to be a new type of offense, threatened with a fine, arrest or restriction of freedom.
The introduction of such a change is wanted by police trade unionists.
The idea went to the Sejm Committee on Petitions.
“The case is serious, because already every year more than half a million cases of wrongdoing go to Polish courts,” we read.
“Rzeczpospolita” has determined that the petition, which the Independent Police Union writes to MPs on the amendment of the code of offences, has a chance to succeed.
The authors of the petition propose a new wording of the article. 54a of the Code of Infractions.
It would read: "A person who does not submit to the demand or order of a public official, issued within the limits and under the provisions of the Act, shall be punishable by arrest, fine or restriction of liberty."
“Par. 3 of this provision speaks of an identical penalty for those who, without following orders, will prevent or hinder the performance of official activities," the journal reports.
The sociologist Andrzej Kowalski told Rzeczpospolita that although he agrees with the main message of the proposal, he fears that if implemented, he can be used in political matters of manifestations.
“In situations of libertarian demonstrations, this would be unfavorable and instead of mitigating the situation, even to exacerbate it,” he adds.
