Görlitz in Germany offers free accommodation for the review
Free accommodation in exchange for an opinion – such an extraordinary offer was prepared for the German visitors Görlitz.
The actions are to help fight the progressive decline in the number of inhabitants of the city.
Görlitz is Germany's easternmost city.
The beautiful pastel old town attracts 140 thousand tourists every year.
However, as The Guardian writes, the city is struggling with considerable problems.
In Görlitz there are the lowest wages in Germany.
The city is also struggling with a steady loss of population.
After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, most of them left for the west of the country, which translated into a 25 percent decline in the city's population.
In 2013, it amounted to 54 thousand people.
Wanting to fight depopulation, officials came up with the idea to start offering free monthly accommodation in the city.
So far, 150 applications have been submitted to the program.
Two-thirds of them were laid by residents of large cities.
The program was also of interest to people from Hungary, the Czech Republic, the United States and the United Kingdom.
“When we applied, we thought the program was to convince people to move to Görlitz,” said one of the project’s participants.
"Now we feel it doesn't matter if we stay here after four weeks or not," he added.
The city has seven thousand free housing, and unemployment is three times higher than the national average.
Although the city authorities hope that some will move permanently, the main goal of the program is to get the opinion of the participants in the program.
The information collected from the interviews and questionnaires is intended to help revive smaller German cities.
"We want to know more about what people need, and if they decide to move - about what their motivation was," said Robert Knippschild, responsible for the program.
Other cities have already experimented with ideas to lure new residents, offering them incentives in the form of accommodation.
The first was Detroit, which introduced a program to pay promising young professionals for life and work in the city for a year.
Today, such solutions are used in many places, from the Greek island of Antikythera to Candela in Italy, or in the American Tulsa in the state of Oklahoma.
